Week 3 :
understanding of lists, tuples, sets, dictionary, String Methods, Slicing, f-formatting, Big O notations : Time and space complexity
Collections and types : Lists, Tuples, Sets, Dictionaries, they are used to managed the large data like storing multiple values in 1 variable
the best way of understanding is to compare
1. Lists
books = ["Python", "Java", "Oracle"]
Index: (in memory)
0 -> Python
1 -> Java
2 -> Oracle
books[0] = Python, books[-1] = Oracle

books[1] = "C++"   - Lists are mutable.
Python
C++
Oracle

books.append("SQL")
Python
C++
Oracle
SQL           -Append always adds at the end.

books.remove("Oracle")    -Remove by value
books.pop(2)              -Remove by index
del books[1]              -Delete
books.clear()             -Clear
len(books)                - length

append()	-Add item
insert()	-Insert item
remove()	-Remove value
pop()	    -Remove by index
clear()	    -Empty list
sort()	    -Sort
reverse()	-Reverse
copy()	    -Copy
count()	    -Count occurrences
index()	    -Find position

2. Tuple (it is almost identical to list, the difference is you cannot modify it)
book = ("Python", "Java", "Oracle")
book[0] = "SQL"   - this gives TypeError because tuples are immutable.
Ex: Date of birth, Longitudes, latitudes
- only 2 methods
count()
index()

| List         | Tuple       |
|--------------|-------------|
| Mutable      | Immutable   |
| Faster? No   | Yes         |
| More memory  | Less memory |
| Many methods | Very few    |

3. Set - to have a unique value in the values - these are unordered, mutable, unique
books = {"Python", "Java", "Python", "Oracle"}
Python
Java
Oracle

books.add("SQL")      - adding
books.remove("Java")  - removing
books.discard("ABC")  - discarding   (difference is remove throws error and discard don't

4. Dictionary  - has key, value - according to the key we need to assign value
employee = {
    "name":"John",
    "salary":50000,
    "department":"IT"
}
Key -> Value
name -> John
salary -> 50000
department -> IT

employee["salary"] -> 50000
employee["salary"] = 70000  - modify
employee["city"] = "Lusaka" - add
del employee["city"]      - delete
for key in employee:
    print(key)            - using loops
->name
  salary
  department

employee.keys()         - for keys
employee.values()       - for values
employee.items()        - for both

Comprehension - a powerful feature


| Feature    | List | Tuple | Set  | Dictionary        |
| Syntax     | []   | ()    | {}   | {key: value}      |
|------------|------|-------|------|-------------------|
| Ordered    | Y    | Y     | NN   | Y                 |
| Mutable    | Y    | NN    | Y    | Y                 |
| Duplicates | Y    | Y     | NN   | Keys NN, Values Y |
| Indexed    | Y    | Y     | NN   | By keys           |

