Big O notations : Time and space complexity
1. Time complexity: measures the time taken for an operation to perform

Big-O notation :
O(1) - (Constant time) : no matter how much data exists, the time taken is once per operation
Ex :
numbers = [10,20,30,40,50]
print(numbers[2])   -- here only 1 operation, directly jumps to the 2nd index
|
|_______ O(1)
|_______
O(log n) - (Logarithmic time) : instead of checking 1 by 1 it cuts the search into half like guessing a number
Ex : Binary search
|    /O(log n)
|  /
|/______ after every consecutive point he value is doubled
O(n^2) (Quadratic) : this is how much time the loop takes
Ex:
numbers = [1,2,3]
for i in numbers:
    for j in numbers:
        print(i, j)

O(n^3) (Qubic) : this is how much time the nested loop takes
Ex:
for i in arr:
    for j in arr:
        for k in arr:
            print(i, j, k)

 - here the
 best case is O(1) and O(log n)
 Fair Case is O(n), O(n^2) and O(n^3)
 Worst case is O(2^n) and O(n!)

2. Space Complexity: How much extra memory an algorithm needs

Big-O notation :
O(1) : memory never grows
Ex :
def add(a, b):
    return a + b

O(m): Extra list grows with input
Ex:
numbers = [1,2,3,4]
copy = []
for n in numbers:
    copy.append(n)  --here the memory is doubled

O(n^2) : memory becomes n*n
Ex:
matrix = []
for i in range(n):
    row = []
    for j in range(n):
        row.append(0)
    matrix.append(row)

Big - O rules :
1. Ignore constants
Ex: for i in range(2*n): -> O(n)
2. Keep the fastest growing term
Ex : O(n² + n + 100)  ->  O(n²)  #this is a dominant term
3. Every variable is separate
Ex :
for i in range(n):
    print(i)
for j in range(m):
    print(j)                    #O(n + m)